article.headline: Georgia 87, Georgia St 48
article.story:
ATHENS, Ga. (AP) -- Kara Braxton and Christi Thomas made the most
of their limited time together.

Braxton had 15 points and 12 rebounds and Thomas added 12
points, leading No. 10 Georgia to a 87-48 victory over Georgia
State on Friday night in the season opener for both teams.

The 6-foot-5 Thomas and the 6-6 Braxton dominated throughout
against the shorter Lady Panthers, helping Georgia to 50-39
advantage in rebounds. Thomas also had seven blocks.

With the lead in double figures most the way, Braxton and Thomas
didn't stay on the court long. Braxton played 20 minutes, and
Thomas 18.

"We didn't get to play that much together, and that's kind of
frustrating," Braxton said. "Everybody needs to get a chance, but
we wanted to be a little selfish."

Braxton was suspended for the final eight games of last season
for violating team rules, but she has worked her way back into
coach Andy Landers' starting lineup.

"You can't play with anybody else like you can play with her,"
Thomas said of Braxton. "It's great having her back."

Holly Coates had 11 points for Georgia State, which has reached
the NCAA tournament the past three seasons after winning the
Atlantic Sun Conference tournament.

Patechia Hartman added 10 for the Panthers, who lost 89-50 last
season to the Bulldogs.

"Our team was in a tough position," Georgia State coach Lea
Henry said. "In the past, when we played teams like this, we have
been competitive. Georgia is just a very physical team that is
taller and quicker."

When Thomas and Braxton went out of the game, Georgia hardly
lost a step. Rebecca Rowsey and Jessica Pierce took over inside,
and guards Janese Hardrick, Sherill Baker, Cori Chambers and Alexis
Kendrick kept the pressure up on the perimeter.

The Panthers finished with 16 turnovers.

"I was a little concerned coming in because the last 10 days
really hadn't been all that great," Landers said. "But I was
proud of the way the team played. If we can stay healthy, I think
we're all excited about the season."

The Bulldogs used a 13-4 run midway through the first half to
take control, jumping to a 26-12 lead. Hardrick keyed the spurt
with a four-point play, hitting a 3-pointer from the top of the key
while getting fouled, then adding a free throw.

The lead reached 20 for the first time on a putback by Braxton,
one of her eight offensive rebounds, and a 15-8 run at the start of
the second half made it 62-32. Georgia State couldn't recover.

"It was great to get back out there," Braxton said. "I missed
a lot of cheap shots in the beginning, but I came back in the
second half and did pretty well."

Landers, entering his 25th season, substituted liberally in the
second half. With only nine players dressed, everybody got at least
18 minutes.

"Hopefully, they won't misplace that confidence," Landers
said. "It was confidence earned because they played hard and
played well. We work for what we get."
